99","1420":"1420","1441":"1441","1440":"1440","1451":"1451","1484":"1484","1450":"1450","1516":"1516","Hertfordshire, England, United Kingdom":"Hertfordshire, England, United Kingdom","Derbyshire, England":"Derbyshire, England","Shropshire, England":"Shropshire, England","Malpas, Cheshire, England":"Malpas, Cheshire, England","England":"England","St. Albans, Hertfordshire, England":"St Albans, Hertfordshire, England, United Kingdom","nameMeanings":[{"name":"Pointer","type":"LAST","attribution":"Dictionary of American Family Names © Patrick Hanks 2003, 2006.","meanings":["English (southeastern): occupational name, either from Middle English <i>pointere</i>, <i>pointour</i> ‘tiler’ (from an unrecorded Middle English <i>pointer</i>, an agent derivative of <i>pointe</i>, <i>poynte</i> ‘tie, lace, or cord, of twisted yarn, silk, or leather’, for a maker of points for fastening hose and doublet together), or sometimes perhaps from Middle English <i>pointer</i> ‘painter’. Compare   Poynter  .","In some cases also an American shortened form (or a very rare German variant) of South German (mainly Bavaria) <b>Pointner</b>, itself a variant of   Paintner  ."],"variants":[{"name":"Poynter","meanings":["English (southern): variant of   Pointer  ."]}]},{"name":"Ellin","type":"FIRST","meanings":["Some consider this the same as Helen, and indeed in Spanish Helen and Ellen are both represented by Elena. A correspondent of Notes and Queries says the name Ellen has no possible connexion with Helen, which is older by a thousand years at least, and that Ellen is the feminine of Alain, Alan, or Allan. It may, however, be the same as Ailean. Ellin, another spelling of Ellen."],"variants":[{"name":"Ailean","meanings":["Gaelic equivalent of <b>Alan</b> ."]},{"name":"Helen","meanings":["vernacular form of the name (Greek <i>Hēlēnē</i>) borne in classical legend by a famous beauty, wife of Menelaus, whose seizure by the Trojan prince Paris sparked off the Trojan War. Her name is of uncertain origin; it may be connected with a word meaning ‘ray’ or ‘sunbeam’ compare Greek <i>hēlios</i> ‘sun’. It has sometimes been taken as connected with the Greek word meaning ‘Greek’, <i>Hellēn</i>, but this is doubtful. In the early Christian period the name was borne by the mother of the Emperor Constantine, who is now usually known by the Latin version of her name, <i>Helena</i>. She is credited with having found the True Cross in Jerusalem. She was born in about  248 , probably in Bithynia. However, in medieval England it was believed that she had been born in Britain, which greatly increased the popularity of the name there."]},{"name":"Elena","meanings":["form of   Helen  , now used quite frequently in the English-speaking world."]}]}],"lifeSummary":"Ellin Pointer was born in 1420, in Shropshire, England as the daughter of --Unknown-- Pointer. She married John Lowe in 1440, in Derbyshire, England. They were the parents of at least 4 sons. She died in 1451, in England, at the age of 31."},"et":{"1420–1451":"1420–1451","1415–1484":"1415–1484","1440–1516":"1440–1516","1440–Male":"1440–Surnud","1441–Male":"1441–Surnud","1450–1499":"1450–1499","1400–Male":"1400–Surnud","1415":"1415","15 September 1440":"15. september 1440","1400":"1400","1499":"1499","1420":"1420","1441":"1441","1440":"1440","1451":"1451","1484":"1484","1450":"1450","1516":"1516","Hertfordshire, England, United Kingdom":"Hertfordshire, Inglismaa, United Kingdom","Derbyshire, England":"Derbyshire, England","Shropshire, England":"Shropshire, England","Malpas, Cheshire, England":"Malpas, Cheshire, England","England":"England","St. Albans, Hertfordshire, England":"St Albans, Hertfordshire, Inglismaa, United Kingdom"},"fi":{"1420–1451":"1420–1451","1415–1484":"1415–1484","1440–1516":"1440–1516","1440–Male":"1440–Kuollut","1441–Male":"1441–Kuollut","1450–1499":"1450–1499","1400–Male":"1400–Kuollut","1415":"1415","15 September 1440":"15. syyskuuta 1440","1400":"1400","1499":"1499","1420":"1420","1441":"1441",